nations=C2=A0are possibl=\r\ne, how is this priority of X combination over Y decided?\n=C2=A0\n&gt;The role y=\r\nou are given is your destiny and how you play it is your free will.\nIn exce=\r\nption cases like suicide, do we say that it&#39;s a destiny or it&#39;s a=C2=A0free=\r\n will used by an individual to run away from suffering?\nThe reason for aski=\r\nng this question is, usually it&#39;s possible to see suicidal tendencies in Jy=\r\notisha. If the indication of prarabdha karma is suicide, then should we con=\r\nsider it as his karma for this life?\n=C2=A0\nThanks & Regards,\n--Murahari\n=\r\n=C2=A0\n\n--- On Fri, 4/2/10, Narasimha PVR Rao &lt;pvr@...&gt; wrote:\n\n\nFr=\r\nom: Narasimha PVR Rao &lt;pvr@...&gt;\nSubject: [vedic-wisdom] Re: Ramana =\r\nMaharshi says Each person had an allotted role to play in this world\nTo: ve=\r\ndic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com\nDate: Friday, April 2, 2010, 11:37 AM\n\n\nNamaste,=\r\n\n\nEveryone plays their allotted role. But the roles are not static. They ar=\r\ne dynamic and may undergo fine-tuning or modification or evolution from tim=\r\ne to time (and life to life) based on how we play our allotted roles. \n\nThe=\r\n role you are given is your destiny and how you play it is your free will. =\r\nHow you play your role now (free will) influences what role you are given i=\r\nn future (destiny).\n\nIf the role given to you (e.g. Arjuna) is to kill your=\r\n guru (Drona) and relatives, you cannot escape it. But you can either do it=\r\n with a hateful mind or a guilty mind or you can do it with a calm mind. If=\r\n the role given to you (e.g. Janaka) is to rule a big kingdom, you cannot e=\r\nscape and do penances in a forest. But you can either rule the kingdom with=\r\n a proud and attached mind or with a calm mind. If the role given to you (e=\r\n.g. Swami Samarth Ramadas) is to guide a mighty king (Shivaji) in resisting=\r\n the invading muslim kings, you cannot escape it. But you can either do it =\r\nwith an attached and agitated mind or a calm mind.\n\nPeople in the examples =\r\nI mentioned above engaged in what may seem like material actions, but they =\r\ndid them after overcoming attachments and with an equanimous mind.\n\nAs I ke=\r\nep saying, what you do is a secondary factor and how you do it is primary. =\r\nEven as we engage in actions that we believe to be our dharma, we should wo=\r\nrk on our attitude and increase surrender. When one has surrendered to god =\r\nand is able to look at pleasure and pain, praise and censure in the same wa=\r\ny, then one&#39;s dharma will be far clearer to one. One whose mind is densely =\r\nconditioned by duality and desires will see one&#39;s dharma through the colori=\r\nng of that conditioning and may misjudge. On the other hand, one with a cle=\r\nar mind with very little conditioning will see one&#39;s dharma clearer.\n\nIn si=\r\nmpler words, one who heavily identifies with the body and wants comforts an=\r\nd pleasures of the body will see one&#39;s dharma from that motivation. One may=\r\n identify with body, with a group of people, with a deity etc. As is the id=\r\nentification, so is the conditioning and so is one&#39;s vision of one&#39;s dharma=\r\n.\n\nThough everyone is playing their allotted role, some have densely condit=\r\nioned minds and unable to see their dharma clearly and pursuing adharma. As=\r\n a result, they may continue to be allotted roles where densely conditioned=\r\n minds restrict their actions, in future.\n\nSome have very clear minds and a=\r\nble to see their dharma clearly and pursuing higher dharma. As a result, th=\r\ney may continue to allotted roles where lighter and lighter mental conditio=\r\nning restricts them and eventually they become free.\n\nOne can try to use fr=\r\nee will to move from the former case to the latter case.\n\nBest regards,\nNar=\r\nasimha\n-------------------------------------------------------------------\n=\r\n=C2=A0 Free Jyotish Software, Free Jyotish Lessons, Jyot