 with an attached and a=\r\ngitated mind or a calm mind.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;People in the examples I mentioned abov=\r\ne engaged in what may seem like material actions, but they did them after o=\r\nvercoming attachments and with an equanimous mind.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;As I keep saying,=\r\n what you do is a secondary factor and how you do it is primary. Even as we=\r\n engage in actions that we believe to be our dharma, we should work on our =\r\nattitude and increase surrender. When one has surrendered to god and is abl=\r\ne to look at pleasure and pain, praise and censure in the same way, then on=\r\ne&#39;s dharma will be far clearer to one. One whose mind is densely conditione=\r\nd by duality and desires will see one&#39;s dharma through the coloring of that=\r\n conditioning and may misjudge. On the other hand, one with a clear mind wi=\r\nth very little conditioning will see one&#39;s dharma clearer.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;In simple=\r\nr words, one who heavily identifies with the body and wants\n comforts and p=\r\nleasures of the body will see one&#39;s dharma from that motivation. One may id=\r\nentify with body, with a group of people, with a deity etc. As is the ident=\r\nification, so is the conditioning and so is one&#39;s vision of one&#39;s dharma.&lt;B=\r\nR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Though everyone is playing their allotted role, some have densely con=\r\nditioned minds and unable to see their dharma clearly and pursuing adharma.=\r\n As a result, they may continue to be allotted roles where densely conditio=\r\nned minds restrict their actions, in future.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Some have very clear mi=\r\nnds and able to see their dharma clearly and pursuing higher dharma. As a r=\r\nesult, they may continue to allotted roles where lighter and lighter mental=\r\n conditioning restricts them and eventually they become free.&lt;BR&gt;&lt;BR&gt;One ca=\r\nn try to use free will to move from the former case to the latter case.&lt;BR&gt;=\r\n&lt;BR&gt;Best regards,&lt;BR